[Student "S"]
{North is to play 6NT. East leads the \CK.

You have 11 winners, 3 \Ss, 4 \Hs, 3 \Ds and 1 \C. If either \Ss or \Ds split 3-3 that would give you your 12th trick. If both split 3-3 you can make all thirteen tricks. 

As you see, neither of them splits. However since one defender, West in this case, holds both Guards you should be able to squeeze him. 

Visualize what would happen, though, if you win the first trick and then play your 4 \H winners. West would play his 3 \Cs and 2 \Hs on those 5 tricks and he would not be squeezed. The problem is that you have to <b>RECTIFY THE COUNT</b>. 

To rectify the count you have to lose all the tricks you can afford to lose, which in this hand is exactly one trick. So you duck the \CK and win the next trick when East continues with the \CQ. 

AHA! The count is rectified, so now you play your \H winners.

West has no problems on the first 3, he just plays his 2 \Hs and 1 \C. 

Here is the situation just as you are about to play the Squeeze Card, the \HA.

You will toss dummy's \C8 and West will have to decide whether it is better for him to throw a \S or a \D. He doesn't know that discarding either one is going to hand you the contract, so he will probably discard a \D.  }
[Play "W"]CK

